In Rust, the concept of "arc" usually refers to the `Arc<T>` type from the `std::sync` module, which provides a thread-safe reference-counted shared pointer. It allows safely sharing data across multiple threads, wherein each thread with a reference to the data increments the reference count; when no more references exist, the data is deallocated. 

When we talk about building a "custom arc" in Rust, it implies creating a custom implementation to support thread-safe reference counting.

Here's a basic outline of creating a custom arc:

1. Define a struct that will hold our reference-counted data. This struct will include a `data: T` field to hold the actual data, and a `ref_count: AtomicUsize` field, which will keep track of the reference count while allowing atomic operations.

2. Implement the `Clone` trait for the struct so that it can be easily cloned when a new thread needs access.

3. Implement the `Drop` trait for the struct to decrement the reference count when a reference goes out of scope, and to safely deallocate the data if the reference count reaches zero.

Here's an example of a simple custom arc implementation:

```rust
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering};
use std::ops::{Deref, Drop};

struct CustomArc<T> {
    data: *const T,
    ref_count: *const AtomicUsize,
}

unsafe impl<T: Sync> Send for CustomArc<T> {}
unsafe impl<T: Sync> Sync for CustomArc<T> {}

impl<T> Clone for CustomArc<T> {
    fn clone(&self) -> Self {
        unsafe {
            (*self.ref_count).fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
        }
        CustomArc {
            data: self.data,
            ref_count: self.ref_count,
        }
    }
}

impl<T> Deref for CustomArc<T> {
    type Target = T;

    fn deref(&self) -> &Self::Target {
        unsafe { &*self.data }
    }
}

impl<T> Drop for CustomArc<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        unsafe {
            if (*self.ref_count).fetch_sub(1, Ordering::Release) == 1 {
                std::sync::atomic::fence(std::sync::atomic::Ordering::Acquire);
                Box::from_raw(self.data as *mut T);
                Box::from_raw(self.ref_count as *mut AtomicUsize);
            }
        }
    }
}

impl<T> CustomArc<T> {
    fn new(data: T) -> Self {
        let boxed_data = Box::new(data);
        let boxed_ref_count = Box::new(AtomicUsize::new(1));

        CustomArc {
            data: Box::into_raw(boxed_data),
            ref_count: Box::into_raw(boxed_ref_count),
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let data = CustomArc::new("Hello, world!");
    let cloned_data = data.clone();
    println!("{}", *data);
    println!("{}", *cloned_data);
}
```

This example defines the `CustomArc` struct and implements the `Clone`, `Deref`, and `Drop` traits. The `new` function initializes and returns a `CustomArc`. Note that the implementation above is minimal and may not cover all edge cases, but it demonstrates the basic idea of building a custom arc in Rust.

To generate a 2D Voronoi mesh with boundary clipping in C#, you can use a third-party library like the Delaunay-Voronoi diagram (2d) library. This library calculates the Delaunay triangulation and the Voronoi diagram of a given set of 2D points.

1. First, download the Delaunay-Voronoi diagram (2d) library from https://github.com/Biarity/DelaunayVoronoi.
2. Add it to your C# project.

Here's an example of how to use the library to generate a 2D Voronoi mesh with boundary clipping:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Drawing;
using DelaunayVoronoi;

namespace VoronoiMeshExample
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            // Define the boundary rectangle for clipping
            var boundary = new Rectangle(0, 0, 100, 100);

            // Create some random points within the boundary
            var points = GenerateRandomPoints(100, boundary);

            // Create the Delaunay triangulation and Voronoi diagram
            var delaunay = new DelaunayTriangulator();
            var voronoi = new VoronoiDiagram(points);

            // Generate the Voronoi mesh with boundary clipping
            var clippedEdges = voronoi.ClipEdgesToBoundary(boundary);

            // Print the clipped Voronoi edges
            foreach (var edge in clippedEdges)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"Edge: ({edge.Point1.X}, {edge.Point1.Y}) to ({edge.Point2.X}, {edge.Point2.Y})");
            }
        }

        private static List<Point> GenerateRandomPoints(int count, Rectangle boundary)
        {
            var random = new Random();
            var points = new List<Point>();

            for (int i = 0; i < count; i++)
            {
                int x = random.Next(boundary.Left, boundary.Right);
                int y = random.Next(boundary.Top, boundary.Bottom);
                points.Add(new Point(x, y));
            }

            return points;
        }
    }
}
```

This example demonstrates how to create a 2D Voronoi mesh with boundary clipping in C#. It first defines a boundary rectangle for clipping, generates a set of random points within the boundary, and then creates the Delaunay triangulation and Voronoi diagram of the point set. The Voronoi edges are then clipped to the boundary and printed.

