You can write a simple JavaScript script like this to replace words in an HTML document using a table (in this case, an object that maps the words to their replacements).

1. Include the following script inside a `<script>` tag in your HTML file:

```javascript
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
  const replacements = {
    "word1": "replacement1",
    "word2": "replacement2",
    // Add more words and replacements here
  };

  function replaceWords(node) {
    if (node.nodeType === Node.TEXT_NODE) {
      Object.keys(replacements).forEach((word) => {
        const regex = new RegExp('\\b' + word + '\\b', 'g');
        node.textContent = node.textContent.replace(regex, replacements[word]);
      });
    } else if (node.nodeType === Node.ELEMENT_NODE) {
      node.childNodes.forEach(replaceWords);
    }
  }

  replaceWords(document.body);
});
```

2. Replace "word1", "replacement1", "word2", "replacement2" in the `replacements` object with the words you want to replace and their respective replacements.

3. When you load the HTML document in the browser, the script replaces all occurrences of the specified words with their replacements.

Note: This script will only run if the page is loaded in a web browser. To test it, you can create an HTML file with some text containing the words you want to replace, and then run the file in the browser.

Here is a Delphi code snippet for finding the intersection of two arrays ar1 and ar2:

```
var
  ar1, ar2, intersect: TArray<Integer>;
  i, j, k: Integer;
begin
  // Initialize input arrays
  ar1 := [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];
  ar2 := [2, 4, 6, 8, 10];

  // Initialize output array
  SetLength(intersect, Min(Length(ar1), Length(ar2)));
  k := 0;

  // Loop through arrays and find common elements
  for i := Low(ar1) to High(ar1) do
  begin
    for j := Low(ar2) to High(ar2) do
    begin
      if ar1[i] = ar2[j] then
      begin
        intersect[k] := ar1[i];
        Inc(k);
        Break;
      end;
    end;
  end;

  // Copy the intersection array to a new array with the correct length
  SetLength(intersect, k);

  // Print the intersection array
  for i := Low(intersect) to High(intersect) do
    WriteLn(intersect[i]);
end.
```

In this example, we initialize the input arrays ar1 and ar2 with some sample data. We then create a new array called intersect to store the common elements of ar1 and ar2. We loop through both arrays and compare each element, adding it to the intersect array if it is found in both arrays. Finally, we resize the intersect array to remove any empty space and print its contents.

Note that this implementation has a time complexity of O(n^2), which may not be efficient for large arrays. There are faster algorithms available for finding the intersection of arrays, such as using a hash set or sorting the arrays and performing a merging algorithm.

