    </footer>
</body>

</html>
```

2. Create a new CSS file (e.g. `styles.css`), and style the page to your preferred look:

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: auto;
}

header, footer {
    text-align: center;
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    padding: 1rem;
}

.main {
    margin-top: 2rem;
}

table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
}

table th, table td {
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    padding: 10px;
    text-align: left;
}

table th {
    background-color: #efefef;
}
```

3. Create a new JavaScript file (e.g. `scripts.js`) to handle interaction with the data and the page elements:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const searchButton = document.getElementById('search-button');
    const searchInput = document.getElementById('search-input');
    const resultsTable = document.getElementById('results-table');

    const data = [
        // Example data, which can be replaced by actual data from a backend API or a database
        { id: 1, name: 'John Doe', email: 'john.doe@example.com', phone: '555-123456' },
        { id: 2, name: 'Jane Doe', email: 'jane.doe@example.com', phone: '555-987654' }
    ];

    searchButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const searchValue = searchInput.value.trim();
        const results = data.filter(item => item.name.toLowerCase().includes(searchValue.toLowerCase()));
        displayResults(results);
    });

    function displayResults(results) {
        resultsTable.innerHTML = '';

        for (const result of results) {
            const row = document.createElement('tr');
            row.innerHTML = `
                <td>${result.id}</td>
                <td>${result.name}</td>
                <td>${result.email}</td>
                <td>${result.phone}</td>
            `;
            resultsTable.appendChild(row);
        }
    }
});
```

Note that the example data provided in the `scripts.js` file is just an example. In a real project, you'd probably use an API or fetch the data from the actual database.

To run this example on your machine, create the three different files as described (`index.html`, `styles.css`, and `scripts.js`) with the provided content, and then open the `index.html` file in your web browser.

Creating a simple Gioui golang todos app involves several steps. Gioui is a modern UI library for Golang that uses GPU-efficient rendering techniques.

1. Install the Golang and Gioui library: Make sure you have Golang installed on your system, preferably the latest version. You can get it from [here](https://golang.org/doc/install). Then, install the Gioui library using the following command:

   ```
   go get gioui.org/cmd/gio@latest
   ```

2. Create a file called `main.go` and open it in your favorite text editor for Golang. Here's a simple todo app that you can use as a starting point:

   ```go
   package main

   import (
   	"gioui.org/app"
   	"gioui.org/layout"
   	"gioui.org/unit"
   	"gioui.org/widget"
   )

   func main() {
   	go func() {
   		w := app.NewWindow(app.Title("Todos"), app.Size(unit.Dp(320), unit.Dp(480)))
   		todos := make([]string, 0)
   		newTask := &widget.Editor{}
   		list := &layout.List{}
   		for e := range w.Events() {
   			if e, ok := e.(app.UpdateEvent); ok {
   				gtx := layout.NewContext(&e.Config, e.Queue, e.Size)
   				inputField := layout.Rigid(
   					func(gtx layout.Context) layout.Dimensions {
   						newTask.Layout(gtx, &e.Config)
   						if newTask.Submit() {
   							text := newTask.Text()
   							todos = append(todos, text)
   							newTask.SetText("")
   						}
   						return layout.Dimensions{}
   					})
   				todoList := layout.Flexed(1,
   					func(gtx layout.Context) layout.Dimensions {
   						return list.Layout(gtx, len(todos), func(gtx layout.Context, index int) layout.Dimensions {
   							text := todos[index]
   							widget.Label{Align: layout.Start}.Layout(gtx, &e.Config, text)
   							return layout.Dimensions{}
   						})
   					})
   				layout.Flex{
   					Axis:    layout.Vertical,
   					Spacing: layout.SpaceEvenly,
   				}.Layout(gtx, inputField, todoList)
   				w.Update(gtx)
   			}
   		}
   	}()

   	app.Main()
   }
   ```

3. Compile and run the app using the Gioui command:

   ```
   gio run main.go
   ```

The provided example creates a simple todo app with an editor for entering new tasks and a list to display the existing tasks. Feel free to extend and modify the example to meet your specific requirements.

To learn more about the Gioui library, check out the [Gioui documentation](https://gioui.org/docs/getting-started).

